<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1878,2015]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,213]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="205" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">
When mounted on slides it is easy to identify specimens as belonging to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Winnertz" authorityYear="1867" box="[1079,1180,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1079,1180,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">Bradysia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The main character is the shape of the tibial organ on the fore tibia, consisting of a comb-like row of bristles on a united base, distinctly separated from the ground hair of the tibia. Additional characters are a 3-segmented palpus with at least 2 bristles on the basal segment, bare posterior wing veins and a rather long R1 (different from 
<taxonomicName box="[1119,1265,1987,2010]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Scatopsciara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1119,1265,1987,2010]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">Scatopsciara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The genus is distributed worldwide in all zoogeographic zones with plant growth and is likely to be the most species-rich sciarid genus of all.
</paragraph>
